result.execSummary:
The defendant Kristin Elizabeth Engler was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Robbery with Threat of Force, a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Pay restitution to the Mobile Gas Station in the stipulated amount of $650.00.  CASH BAIL ON DEPOSIT TO APPLY.
Court ordered the defendant to pay the DNA surcharge, costs and disbursements; CASH BAIL ON DEPOSIT TO APPLY.

Seek and maintain employment.
Be given job and vocational training.

The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms or body armor.   Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility and that all terms and conditions of bail are to continue.
Undergo a mental health evaluation; follow any treatment recommended.

No contact with Seema V.
No contact with the Mobil Gas Station at 6611 South 27th Street, City of Franklin, county of Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
No controlled substances other than those legally prescribed for defendant by a duly licensed physician for her mental or physical needs; take only as prescribed and only for as long as deemed medically reasonable and necessary.
No alcohol.

Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample.
Cognitive thinking intervention counseling.

AODA assessment; treatment, if needed. 
Urine screens to ensure compliance.

timeConds.notes: 9 months to be served by defendant with Huber for work and release to the Day Reporting Center.  Court stayed report date to 5:00 p.m. on 7/27/15.  The balance of 90 days was stayed to be used at the discretion of the agent for any sanctions.  In the alternative, if defendant is non-compliant, the Court ordered revocation of defendant's probation in lieu of the 90 days condition time.
